# Flutter Button Cursor Pointer Rule

## Requirement

ALL interactive buttons and clickable widgets MUST show a pointer cursor when enabled on web platforms.

## Implementation

### For Custom Buttons (InkWell, GestureDetector)

```dart
// ❌ BAD - No cursor pointer
InkWell(
  onTap: onPressed,
  child: Container(...),
)

// ✅ GOOD - With cursor pointer
InkWell(
  onTap: onPressed,
  mouseCursor: onPressed != null 
    ? SystemMouseCursors.click 
    : SystemMouseCursors.forbidden,
  child: Container(...),
)
```

### For Material Buttons

```dart
// ❌ BAD - Default cursor behavior
ElevatedButton(
  onPressed: onPressed,
  child: Text('Click Me'),
)

// ✅ GOOD - With explicit cursor
ElevatedButton(
  onPressed: onPressed,
  mouseCursor: onPressed != null 
    ? SystemMouseCursors.click 
    : SystemMouseCursors.forbidden,
  child: Text('Click Me'),
)
```

### For Container-based Buttons

```dart
// ❌ BAD - No cursor feedback
GestureDetector(
  onTap: onPressed,
  child: Container(...),
)

// ✅ GOOD - With cursor feedback
MouseRegion(
  cursor: onPressed != null 
    ? SystemMouseCursors.click 
    : SystemMouseCursors.forbidden,
  child: GestureDetector(
    onTap: onPressed,
    child: Container(...),
  ),
)
```

## Cursor Types

- **`SystemMouseCursors.click`**: For enabled buttons
- **`SystemMouseCursors.forbidden`**: For disabled buttons
- **`SystemMouseCursors.basic`**: For non-interactive elements

## Pattern for Custom Widgets

```dart
class CustomButton extends StatelessWidget {
  final VoidCallback? onPressed;
  
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MouseRegion(
      cursor: onPressed != null 
        ? SystemMouseCursors.click 
        : SystemMouseCursors.forbidden,
      child: InkWell(
        onTap: onPressed,
        mouseCursor: onPressed != null 
          ? SystemMouseCursors.click 
          : SystemMouseCursors.forbidden,
        child: // ... button content
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

## Why This Matters

- **Web UX**: Users expect pointer cursor on clickable elements
- **Accessibility**: Clear visual feedback for interactive elements
- **Professional**: Matches web standards and user expectations
- **Disabled State**: Shows forbidden cursor when button is disabled